ues of memory, mourning and trauma, together with questions of gender and genre representation, have been dealt with in the cinema that followed the advent of democracy in 1983. By means of a solid theoretical underpinning and the thorough textual analysis of some canonical films, such as La historia oficial and Sur, and others less well known, for example En retirada, La amiga, El acto en cuestión, the book offers new insights into contemporary Latin American cinema. Constanza Burucúa, having completed her PhD at the University of Warwick, is an independent film producer in Caracas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGender identity in motion pictures. 0aMemory in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryzArgentina. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aArgentine Cinema.  aContemporary Latin American Cinema.  aDirty War.  aGender.  aHistorical Representations.  aMemory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846157097?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846157097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846157097/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles